The best approach for your .NET 10 project is to adopt the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already wraps the full `System.IO` surface.

## Recommended approach

**1. Install the package:**
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

**2. Register in DI:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, "content");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

## Why not a custom wrapper?

| Custom `IFileSystemWrapper` | `System.IO.Abstractions` |
|-|-|
| You maintain it | Community-maintained, complete |
| Only covers methods you wrap today | Covers the entire `System.IO` surface |
| No built-in test helpers | Ships `MockFileSystem` with full in-memory FS |

---

Your `ReportGenerator.cs` also uses `DateTime.UtcNow` and `Environment.*` — those need separate abstractions (`TimeProvider` for time, a custom `IEnvironmentProvider` for environment variables) if you want full testability. Want me to generate wrappers for those too?
